# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: transcription-biology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] Trifluoroethanol is produced industrially by hydrogenation or the hydride reduction of derivatives of trifluoroacetic acid, such as the esters or acyl chloride.
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] TFEA can also be prepared by hydrogenolysis of compounds of generic formula CF3−CHOH−OR (where R is hydrogen or an alkyl group containing from one to eight carbon atoms), in the presence of a palladium containing catalyst deposited on activated charcoal.
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] As a co-catalyst for this conversion tertiary aliphatic amines like triethylamine are commonly employed.
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] Trifluoroethanol is used as a specialized solvent in organic chemistry.
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] Oxidations of sulfur compounds using hydrogen peroxide are effectively conducted in TFEA.
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] It competitively inhibits alcohol dehydrogenase for example.
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] TFEA forms complexes with Lewis bases such as THF or pyridine through hydrogen bonding, yielding 1:1 adducts.
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] It is classified as a hard Lewis acid and its acceptor properties are discussed in the ECW model yielding EA = 2.07 and CA = 1.06.
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] TFEA can be used in biochemical experiments to stabilize alpha helix.
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] There are also stable beta sheets in TFEA, suggesting that TFEA stabilizes the secondary structure the sequence has a preference for.
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] Oxidation of trifluoroethanol yields trifluoroacetic acid.
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] It also serves as a source of the trifluoroethoxy group for various chemical reactions (Still-Gennari modification of HWE reaction).
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] 2,2,2-Trifluoroethyl vinyl ether, an inhaled drug introduced clinically under the tradename Fluoromar, features a vinyl ether of trifluorethanol.
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] This species was prepared by the reaction of trifluoroethanol with acetylene.
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] Fluorester (2,2,2-trifluoroethyl methacrylate) is an ester of methacrylic acid and TFEA, which can be used as a monomer in specialty paints.
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] Trifluoroethanol is classified as toxic to blood, the reproductive system, bladder, brain, upper respiratory tract and eyes.
[src:transcription-biology/2-2-2-trifluoroethanol] Research has shown it to be a testicular toxicant in rats and dogs.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] While trying to isolate the bacterial toxin responsible for tuberculosis, W.G.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] Ruppel isolated a novel nucleic acid named tuberculinic acid in 1898 from *Tubercle bacillus*.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] The nucleic acid was found to be unusual, in that it contained in addition to thymine, guanine and cytosine, a methylated nucleotide.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] In 1925, Johnson and Coghill successfully detected a minor amount of a methylated cytosine derivative as a product of hydrolysis of tuberculinic acid with sulfuric acid.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] This report was severely criticized because their identification was based solely on the optical properties of the crystalline picrate, and other scientists failed to reproduce the same result.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] But its existence was ultimately proven in 1948, when Hotchkiss separated the nucleic acids of DNA from calf thymus using paper chromatography, by which he detected a unique methylated cytosine, quite distinct from conventional cytosine and uracil.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] After seven decades, it turned out that it is also a common feature in different RNA molecules, although the precise role is uncertain.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] While spontaneous deamination of cytosine forms uracil, which is recognized and removed by DNA repair enzymes, deamination of 5-methylcytosine forms thymine.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] This conversion of a DNA base from cytosine (C) to thymine (T) can result in a transition mutation.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] In addition, active enzymatic deamination of cytosine or 5-methylcytosine by the APOBEC family of cytosine deaminases could have beneficial implications on various cellular processes as well as on organismal evolution.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] The implications of deamination on 5-hydroxymethylcytosine, on the other hand, remains less understood.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] The NH2 group can be removed (deamination) from 5-methylcytosine to form thymine with use of reagents such as nitrous acid; cytosine deaminates to uracil (U) under similar conditions.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] 5-methylcytosine is resistant to deamination by bisulfite treatment, which deaminates cytosine residues.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] This property is often exploited to analyze DNA cytosine methylation patterns with bisulfite sequencing.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] 5mC marks are placed on genomic DNA via DNA methyltransferases (DNMTs).
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] There are 5 DNMTs in humans: DNMT1, DNMT2, DNMT3A, DNMT3B, and DNMT3L, and in algae and fungi 3 more are present (DNMT4, DNMT5, and DNMT6).
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] DNMT1 contains the replication foci targeting sequence (RFTS) and the CXXC domain which catalyze the addition of 5mC marks.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] RFTS directs DNMT1 to loci of DNA replication to assist in the maintenance of 5mC on daughter strands during DNA replication, whereas CXXC contains a zinc finger domain for *de novo* addition of methylation to the DNA.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] DNMT1 was found to be the predominant DNA methyltransferase in all human tissue.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] Primarily, DNMT3A and DNMT3B are responsible for *de novo* methylation, and DNMT1 maintains the 5mC mark after replication.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] DNMTs can interact with each other to increase methylating capability.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] For example, 2 DNMT3L can form a complex with 2 DNMT3A to improve interactions with the DNA, facilitating the methylation.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] Changes in the expression of DNMT results in aberrant methylation.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] Overexpression produces increased methylation, whereas disruption of the enzyme decreased levels of methylation.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] The mechanism of the addition is as follows: first a cysteine residue on the DNMT's PCQ motif creates a nucleophillic attack at carbon 6 on the cytosine nucleotide that is to be methylated.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] S-Adenosylmethionine then donates a methyl group to carbon 5.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] A base in the DNMT enzyme deprotonates the residual hydrogen on carbon 5 restoring the double bond between carbon 5 and 6 in the ring, producing the 5-methylcytosine base pair.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] After a cytosine is methylated to 5mC, it can be reversed back to its initial state via multiple mechanisms.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] Passive DNA demethylation by dilution eliminates the mark gradually through replication by a lack of maintenance by DNMT.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] In active DNA demethylation, a series of oxidations converts it to 5-hydroxymethylcytosine (5hmC), 5-formylcytosine (5fC), and 5-carboxylcytosine (5caC), and the latter two are eventually excised by thymine DNA glycosylase (TDG), followed by base excision repair (BER) to restore the cytosine.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] TDG knockout produced a 2-fold increase of 5fC without any statistically significant change to levels of 5hmC, indicating 5mC must be iteratively oxidized at least twice before its full demethylation.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] The oxidation occurs through the TET (Ten-eleven translocation) family dioxygenases (TET enzymes) which can convert 5mC, 5hmC, and 5fC to their oxidized forms.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] However, the enzyme has the greatest preference for 5mC and the initial reaction rate for 5hmC and 5fC conversions with TET2 are 4.9-7.6 fold slower.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] TET requires Fe(II) as cofactor, and oxygen and α-ketoglutarate (α-KG) as substrates, and the latter substrate is generated from isocitrate by the enzyme isocitrate dehydrogenase (IDH).
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] Cancer however can produce 2-hydroxyglutarate (2HG) which competes with α-KG, reducing TET activity, and in turn reducing conversion of 5mC to 5hmC.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] In cancer, DNA can become both overly methylated, termed hypermethylation, and under-methylated, termed hypomethylation.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] CpG islands overlapping gene promoters are *de novo* methylated resulting in aberrant inactivation of genes normally associated with growth inhibition of tumors (an example of hypermethylation).
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] Comparing tumor and normal tissue, the former had elevated levels of the methyltransferases DNMT1, DNMT3A, and mostly DNMT3B, all of which are associated with the abnormal levels of 5mC in cancer.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] Repeat sequences in the genome, including satellite DNA, Alu, and long interspersed elements (LINE), are often seen hypomethylated in cancer, resulting in expression of these normally silenced genes, and levels are often significant markers of tumor progression.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] It has been hypothesized that there a connection between the hypermethylation and hypomethylation; over activity of DNA methyltransferases that produce the abnormal *de novo* 5mC methylation may be compensated by the removal of methylation, a type of epigenetic repair.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] However, the removal of methylation is inefficient resulting in an overshoot of genome-wide hypomethylation.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] The contrary may also be possible; over expression of hypomethylation may be silenced by genome-wide hypermethylation.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] Cancer hallmark capabilities are likely acquired through epigenetic changes that alter the 5mC in both the cancer cells and in surrounding tumor-associated stroma within the tumor microenvironment.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] The anticancer drug Cisplatin has been reported to react with 5mC.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] "Epigenetic age" refers to the connection between chronological age and levels of DNA methylation in the genome.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] Coupling the levels of DNA methylation, in specific sets of CpGs called "clock CpGs", with algorithms that regress the typical levels of collective genome-wide methylation at a given chronological age, allow for epigenetic age prediction.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] During youth (0–20 years old), changes in DNA methylation occur at a faster rate as development and growth progresses, and the changes begin to slow down at older ages.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] Multiple epigenetic age estimators exist.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] Horvath's clock measures a multi-tissue set of 353 CpGs, half of which positively correlate with age, and the other half negatively, to estimate the epigenetic age.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] Hannum's clock utilizes adult blood samples to calculate age based on an orthogonal basis of 71 CpGs.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] Levine's clock, known as DNAm PhenoAge, depends on 513 CpGs and surpasses the other age estimators in predicting mortality and lifespan, yet displays bias with non-blood tissues.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] There are reports of age estimators with the methylation state of only one CpG in the gene ELOVL2.
[src:transcription-biology/5-methylcytosine] Estimation of age allows for prediction lifespan through expectations of age related conditions that individuals may be subject to based on their 5mC methylation markers.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] In aqueous solution 8-hydroxyquinoline has a pKa value of ca.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] 9.9 It reacts with metal ions, losing the proton and forming 8-hydroxyquinolinato-chelate complexes.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] The aluminium complex, is a common component of organic light-emitting diodes (OLEDs).
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] Substituents on the quinoline ring affect the luminescence properties.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] In its photo-induced excited-state, 8-hydroxyquinoline converts to zwitterionic isomers, in which the hydrogen atom is transferred from oxygen to nitrogen.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] 8-hydroxyquinoline was first obtained by Hugo Weidel and his student Albert Cobenzl in 1880.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] They decarboxylated so-called oxycinchoninic acid (from cinchonine) and characterized the resulting compound as melting at about 70°C.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] They identified that the hydroxy group is on the benzene ring (but not its particular place) and called the compound **oxyquinoline** and **α-quinophenol**.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] In the following year more chemists found other ways to make the compound.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] Zdenko Hans Skraup discovered a way to synthesize substituted quinolines from substituted phenols and described three isomers of oxyquinoline, identifying the structure of 8-hydroxyquinoline.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] Otto Fischer and his student Karl Bedall made the compound from a sulphonic acid independently at about the same time, but misidentified its structure.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] By 1888 azo dyes were made from the compound.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] In the 1920s insoluble chelates of 8-hydroxyquinoline were discovered.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] The complexes as well as the heterocycle itself exhibit antiseptic, disinfectant, and pesticide properties, functioning as a transcription inhibitor.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] Its solution in alcohol is used in liquid bandages.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] It once was of interest as an anti-cancer drug.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] A thiol analogue, 8-mercaptoquinoline is also known.
[src:transcription-biology/8-hydroxyquinoline] The roots of the invasive plant *Centaurea diffusa* release 8-hydroxyquinoline, which has a negative effect on plants that have not co-evolved with it.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:transcription-biology/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:transcription-biology/abortive-initiation] Abortive initiation occurs prior to promoter clearance.
[src:transcription-biology/abortive-initiation] Abortive initiation is a normal process of transcription and occurs both *in vitro* and *in vivo*.
[src:transcription-biology/abortive-initiation] After each nucleotide-addition step in initial transcription, RNA polymerase, stochastically, can proceed on the pathway toward promoter escape (productive initiation) or can release the RNA product and revert to the RNA polymerase-promoter open complex (abortive initiation).
[src:transcription-biology/abortive-initiation] During this early stage of transcription, RNA polymerase enters a phase during which dissociation of the transcription complex energetically competes with the elongation process.
[src:transcription-biology/abortive-initiation] Abortive cycling is not caused by strong binding between the initiation complex and the promoter.
[src:transcription-biology/abortive-initiation] For many years, the mechanism by which RNA polymerase moves along the DNA strand during abortive initiation remained elusive.
[src:transcription-biology/abortive-initiation] It had been observed that RNA polymerase did not escape from the promoter during transcription initiation, so it was unknown how the enzyme could read the DNA strand to transcribe it without moving downstream.
[src:transcription-biology/abortive-initiation] This causes the unwound DNA to accumulate within the enzyme, hence the name DNA "scrunching".
[src:transcription-biology/abortive-initiation] A 2006 paper that demonstrated the involvement of DNA scrunching in initial transcription proposed the idea that the stress incurred during DNA scrunching provides the driving force for both abortive initiation and productive initiation.
[src:transcription-biology/abortive-initiation] A companion paper published the same year confirmed that detectable DNA scrunching occurs in 80% of transcription cycles, and is actually estimated to be 100%, given the limitation of the ability to detect rapid scrunching (20% of scrunches have a duration of less than 1 second).
[src:transcription-biology/abortive-initiation] A 2016 paper showed that DNA scrunching also occurs before RNA synthesis during transcription start site selection.
[src:transcription-biology/abortive-initiation] There are no widely accepted functions for the resulting truncated RNA transcripts.
[src:transcription-biology/abortive-initiation] However, a study in 1981 found evidence that there was a relationship between the number of abortive transcripts produced and the time until long RNA strands are successfully produced.
[src:transcription-biology/abortive-initiation] When RNA polymerase undergoes abortive transcription in the presence of ATP, UTP, and GTP, a complex is formed that has a much lower capacity for abortive recycling and a much higher rate of synthesis of the full-length RNA transcript.
[src:transcription-biology/abortive-initiation] A study in 2010 found evidence that these truncated transcripts inhibit termination of RNA synthesis by a RNA hairpin-dependent intrinsic terminator.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] A transcriptional **activator** is a protein (transcription factor) that increases transcription of a gene or set of genes.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activators are considered to have *positive* control over gene expression, as they function to promote gene transcription and, in some cases, are required for the transcription of genes to occur.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Most activators are DNA-binding proteins that bind to enhancers or promoter-proximal elements.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] The DNA site bound by the activator is referred to as an "activator-binding site".
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] The part of the activator that makes protein–protein interactions with the general transcription machinery is referred to as an "activating region" or "activation domain".
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Other activators help promote gene transcription by triggering RNA polymerase to release from the promoter and proceed along the DNA.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] At times, RNA polymerase can pause shortly after leaving the promoter; activators also function to allow these "stalled" RNA polymerases to continue transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] The activity of activators can be regulated.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Some activators have an allosteric site and can only function when a certain molecule binds to this site, essentially turning the activator on.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Post-translational modifications to activators can also regulate activity, increasing or decreasing activity depending on the type of modification and activator being modified.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] In some cells, usually eukaryotes, multiple activators can bind to the binding-site; these activators tend to bind cooperatively and interact synergistically.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activator proteins consist of two main domains: a DNA-binding domain that binds to a DNA sequence specific to the activator, and an activation domain that functions to increase gene transcription by interacting with other molecules.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activator DNA-binding domains come in a variety of conformations, including the helix-turn-helix, zinc finger, and leucine zipper among others.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] These DNA-binding domains are specific to a certain DNA sequence, allowing activators to turn on only certain genes.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activation domains also come in a variety of types that are categorized based on the domain's amino acid sequence, including alanine-rich, glutamine-rich, and acidic domains.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] These domains are not as specific, and tend to interact with a variety of target molecules.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activators can also have allosteric sites that are responsible for turning the activators themselves on and off.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Within the grooves of the DNA double helix, functional groups of the base pairs are exposed.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] The sequence of the DNA thus creates a unique pattern of surface features, including areas of possible hydrogen bonding, ionic bonding, as well as hydrophobic interactions.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activators also have unique sequences of amino acids with side chains that are able to interact with the functional groups in DNA.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Thus, the pattern of amino acid side chains making up an activator protein will be complementary to the surface features of the specific DNA regulatory sequence it was designed to bind to.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] The complementary interactions between the amino acids of the activator protein and the functional groups of the DNA create an "exact-fit" specificity between the activator and its regulatory DNA sequence.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Most activators bind to the major grooves of the double helix, as these areas tend to be wider, but there are some that will bind to the minor grooves.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activator-binding sites may be located very close to the promoter or numerous base pairs away.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] If the regulatory sequence is located far away, the DNA will loop over itself (DNA looping) in order for the bound activator to interact with the transcription machinery at the promoter site.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] In prokaryotes, multiple genes can be transcribed together (operon), and are thus controlled under the same regulatory sequence.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] In eukaryotes, genes tend to be transcribed individually, and each gene is controlled by its own regulatory sequences.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Regulatory sequences where activators bind are commonly found upstream from the promoter, but they can also be found downstream or even within introns in eukaryotes.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Binding of the activator to its regulatory sequence promotes gene transcription by enabling RNA polymerase activity.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] This is done through various mechanisms, such as recruiting transcription machinery to the promoter and triggering RNA polymerase to continue into elongation.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activator-controlled genes require the binding of activators to regulatory sites in order to recruit the necessary transcription machinery to the promoter region.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activator interactions with RNA polymerase are mostly direct in prokaryotes and indirect in eukaryotes.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] In prokaryotes, activators tend to make contact with the RNA polymerase directly in order to help bind it to the promoter.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] In eukaryotes, activators mostly interact with other proteins, and these proteins will then be the ones to interact with the RNA polymerase.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] In prokaryotes, genes controlled by activators have promoters that are unable to strongly bind to RNA polymerase by themselves.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Thus, activator proteins help to promote the binding of the RNA polymerase to the promoter.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] This is done through various mechanisms.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activators may bend the DNA in order to better expose the promoter so the RNA polymerase can bind more effectively.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activators may make direct contact with the RNA polymerase and secure it to the promoter.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] In eukaryotes, activators have a variety of different target molecules that they can recruit in order to promote gene transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] They can recruit other transcription factors and cofactors that are needed in transcription initiation.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activators can recruit molecules known as coactivators.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] These coactivator molecules can then perform functions necessary for beginning transcription in place of the activators themselves, such as chromatin modifications.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] DNA is much more condensed in eukaryotes; thus, activators tend to recruit proteins that are able to restructure the chromatin so the promoter is more easily accessible by the transcription machinery.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Some proteins will rearrange the layout of nucleosomes along the DNA in order to expose the promoter site (ATP-dependent chromatin remodeling complexes).
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Other proteins affect the binding between histones and DNA via post-translational histone modifications, allowing the DNA tightly wrapped into nucleosomes to loosen.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] All of these recruited molecules work together in order to ultimately recruit the RNA polymerase to the promoter site.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activators can promote gene transcription by signaling the RNA polymerase to move beyond the promoter and proceed along the DNA, initiating the beginning of transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] The RNA polymerase can sometimes pause shortly after beginning transcription, and activators are required to release RNA polymerase from this "stalled" state.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Multiple mechanisms exist for releasing these "stalled" RNA polymerases.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activators may act simply as a signal to trigger the continued movement of the RNA polymerase.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] If the DNA is too condensed to allow RNA polymerase to continue transcription, activators may recruit proteins that can restructure the DNA so any blocks are removed.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activators may also promote the recruitment of elongation factors, which are necessary for the RNA polymerase to continue transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] There are different ways in which the activity of activators themselves can be regulated, in order to ensure that activators are stimulating gene transcription at appropriate times and levels.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activator activity can increase or decrease in response to environmental stimuli or other intracellular signals.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activators often must be "turned on" before they can promote gene transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] The activity of activators is controlled by the ability of the activator to bind to its regulatory site along the DNA.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] The DNA-binding domain of the activator has an active form and an inactive form, which are controlled by the binding of molecules known as allosteric effectors to the allosteric site of the activator.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Activators in their inactive form are not bound to any allosteric effectors.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] When inactive, the activator is unable to bind to its specific regulatory sequence in the DNA, and thus has no regulatory effect on the transcription of genes.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] When an allosteric effector binds to the allosteric site of an activator, a conformational change in the DNA-binding domain occurs, which allows the protein to bind to the DNA and increase gene transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Some activators are able to undergo post-translational modifications that have an effect on their activity within a cell.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Processes such as phosphorylation, acetylation, and ubiquitination, among others, have been seen to regulate the activity of activators.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Depending on the chemical group being added, as well as the nature of the activator itself, post-translational modifications can either increase or decrease the activity of an activator.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] For example, acetylation has been seen to increase the activity of some activators through mechanisms such as increasing DNA-binding affinity.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] On the other hand, ubiquitination decreases the activity of activators, as ubiquitin marks proteins for degradation after they have performed their respective functions.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] In prokaryotes, a lone activator protein is able to promote transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] In eukaryotes, usually more than one activator assembles at the binding-site, forming a complex that acts to promote transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] These activators bind cooperatively at the binding-site, meaning that the binding of one activator increases the affinity of the site to bind another activator (or in some cases another transcriptional regulator) thus making it easier for multiple activators to bind at the site.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] In these cases, the activators interact with each other synergistically, meaning that the rate of transcription that is achieved from multiple activators working together is much higher than the additive effects of the activators if they were working individually.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] The breakdown of maltose in *Escherichia coli* is controlled by gene activation.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] The genes that code for the enzymes responsible for maltose catabolism can only be transcribed in the presence of an activator.The activator that controls transcription of the maltose enzymes is "off" in the absence of maltose.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] In its inactive form, the activator is unable to bind to DNA and promote transcription of the maltose genes.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] When maltose is present in the cell, it binds to the allosteric site of the activator protein, causing a conformational change in the DNA-binding domain of the activator.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] This conformational change "turns on" the activator by allowing it to bind to its specific regulatory DNA sequence.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Binding of the activator to its regulatory site promotes RNA polymerase binding to the promoter and thus transcription, producing the enzymes that are needed to break down the maltose that has entered the cell.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] The catabolite activator protein (CAP), otherwise known as cAMP receptor protein (CRP), activates transcription at the *lac* operon of the bacterium *Escherichia coli*.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] Cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) is produced during glucose starvation; this molecule acts as an allosteric effector that binds to CAP and causes a conformational change that allows CAP to bind to a DNA site located adjacent to the lac promoter.
[src:transcription-biology/activator-genetics] CAP then makes a direct protein–protein interaction with RNA polymerase that recruits RNA polymerase to the lac promoter.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The **human immunodeficiency virus** (HIV) is a retrovirus that attacks the immune system.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Without treatment, it can lead to a spectrum of conditions including **acquired immunodeficiency syndrome** (AIDS).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] It can be managed with treatment and become a manageable chronic health condition.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] While there is no cure or vaccine for HIV, antiretroviral treatment can slow the course of the disease, and, if used before significant disease progression, can extend the life expectancy of someone living with HIV to a nearly standard level.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] An HIV-positive person on treatment can expect to live a normal life, and die with the virus, not of it.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Effective treatment for HIV-positive people (people living with HIV) involves a life-long regimen of medicine to suppress the virus, making the viral load undetectable.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Early testing can show if treatment is needed to stop progression and to prevent infecting others.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Treatment is recommended as soon as the diagnosis is made.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] An HIV-positive person who has an undetectable viral load as a result of long-term treatment has effectively no risk of transmitting HIV sexually.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Campaigns by UNAIDS and other organizations around the world have communicated this as Undetectable = Untransmittable.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Without treatment the infection can interfere with the immune system, and eventually progress to AIDS, sometimes taking many years.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Following initial infection an individual may not notice any symptoms, or may experience a brief period of influenza-like illness.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] During this period the person may not know that they are HIV-positive, yet they will be able to pass on the virus.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Typically, this period is followed by a prolonged incubation period with no symptoms.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Eventually the HIV infection increases the risk of developing other infections such as tuberculosis, as well as other opportunistic infections, and tumors which are rare in people who have normal immune function.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The late stage is often also associated with unintended weight loss.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Without treatment, the life expectancy of an individual with HIV is around 11 years.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV is spread primarily by unprotected sex (including anal, oral and vaginal sex), contaminated hypodermic needles or blood transfusions, and from mother to child during pregnancy, delivery, or breastfeeding.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Some bodily fluids, such as saliva, sweat, and tears, do not transmit the virus.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Oral sex has little risk of transmitting the virus.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Ways to avoid catching HIV and preventing the spread include safe sex, treatment to prevent infection ("PrEP"), treatment to stop infection in someone who has been recently exposed ("PEP"), treating those who are infected, and needle exchange programs.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Disease in a baby can often be prevented by giving both the mother and child antiretroviral medication.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Recognized worldwide in the early 1980s, HIV/AIDS has had a large impact on society, both as an illness and as a source of discrimination.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The disease also has large economic impacts.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] There are many misconceptions about HIV/AIDS, such as the belief that it can be transmitted by casual non-sexual contact.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The disease has become subject to many controversies involving religion, including the Catholic Church's position not to support condom use as prevention.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] It has attracted international medical and political attention as well as large-scale funding since it was identified in the 1980s.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV made the jump from other primates to humans in west-central Africa in the early-to-mid-20th century.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in 1981 and its cause—HIV infection—was identified in the early part of the decade.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Between the first time AIDS was readily identified through 2024, the disease is estimated to have caused at least 42.3 million deaths worldwide.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In 2025, 1.2 million people acquired HIV and an estimated 40.9 million people worldwide were living with HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS is considered a pandemic—a disease outbreak which is present over a large area and is actively spreading.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The United States' National Institutes of Health (NIH) and the Gates Foundation have pledged $200 million focused on developing a global cure for AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] There are three main stages of HIV infection: acute infection, clinical latency, and AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The initial period following infection with HIV is called acute HIV, primary HIV or acute retroviral syndrome.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Many individuals develop an influenza-like illness, mononucleosis or glandular fever 2–4 weeks after exposure while others have no significant symptoms.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Symptoms occur in 40–90% of cases and most commonly include fever, large tender lymph nodes, throat inflammation, a rash, headache, tiredness, and/or sores of the mouth and genitals.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The rash, which occurs in 20–50% of cases, presents itself on the trunk and is maculopapular, classically.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Some people also develop opportunistic infections at this stage.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Gastrointestinal symptoms, such as vomiting or diarrhea may occur.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Neurological symptoms of peripheral neuropathy or Guillain–Barré syndrome also occur.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The duration of the symptoms varies, but is usually one or two weeks.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] These symptoms are not often recognized as signs of HIV infection.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Family doctors or hospitals can misdiagnose cases as one of the many common infectious diseases with similar symptoms.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Someone with an unexplained fever who may have been recently exposed to HIV should consider testing to find out if they have been infected.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The initial symptoms are followed by a stage called clinical latency, asymptomatic HIV, or chronic HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Without treatment, this second stage of the natural history of HIV infection can last from about three years to over 20 years (on average, about eight years).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] While typically there are few or no symptoms at first, near the end of this stage many people experience fever, weight loss, gastrointestinal problems and muscle pains.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Between 50% and 70% of people also develop persistent generalized lymphadenopathy, characterized by unexplained, non-painful enlargement of more than one group of lymph nodes (other than in the groin) for over three to six months.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Although most HIV-1 infected individuals have a detectable viral load and in the absence of treatment will eventually progress to AIDS, a small proportion (about 5%) retain high levels of CD4+ T cells (T helper cells) without antiretroviral therapy for more than five years.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] These individuals are classified as "HIV controllers" or long-term nonprogressors (LTNP).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Another group consists of those who maintain a low or undetectable viral load without anti-retroviral treatment, known as "elite controllers" or "elite suppressors".
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] They represent approximately 1 in 300 infected persons.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS) is defined as an HIV infection with either a CD4+ T cell count below 200 cells per microlitre (μL) of blood or the occurrence of specific diseases associated with HIV infection.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In the absence of specific treatment, around half of people infected with HIV develop AIDS within ten years.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The most common initial conditions that alert to the presence of AIDS are pneumocystis pneumonia (40%), cachexia in the form of HIV wasting syndrome (20%), and esophageal candidiasis.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Other common signs include recurrent respiratory tract infections.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Opportunistic infections may be caused by bacteria, viruses, fungi, and parasites that are normally controlled by the immune system.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Which infections occur depends partly on what organisms are common in the person's environment.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] These infections may affect nearly every organ system.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] People with AIDS have an increased risk of developing various viral-induced cancers, including Kaposi's sarcoma, Burkitt's lymphoma, primary central nervous system lymphoma, and cervical cancer.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Kaposi's sarcoma is the most common cancer, occurring in 10% to 20% of people with HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The second-most common cancer is lymphoma, which is the cause of death of nearly 16% of people with AIDS and is the initial sign of AIDS in 3% to 4%.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Both these cancers are associated with human herpesvirus 8 (HHV-8).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Cervical cancer occurs more frequently in those with AIDS because of its association with human papillomavirus (HPV).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Conjunctival cancer (of the layer that lines the inner part of eyelids and the white part of the eye) is also more common in those with HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Additionally, people with AIDS frequently have systemic symptoms such as prolonged fevers, sweats (particularly at night), swollen lymph nodes, chills, weakness, and unintended weight loss.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Diarrhea is another common symptom, present in about 90% of people with AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] They can also be affected by diverse psychiatric and neurological symptoms independent of opportunistic infections and cancers.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV is spread by three main routes: sexual contact, significant exposure to infected body fluids or tissues, and from mother to child during pregnancy, delivery, or breastfeeding (known as vertical transmission).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] There is no risk of acquiring HIV if exposed to feces, nasal secretions, saliva, sputum, sweat, tears, urine, or vomit unless these are contaminated with blood.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] It is also possible to be co-infected by more than one strain of HIV—a condition known as HIV superinfection.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The most frequent mode of transmission of HIV is through sexual contact with an infected person.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] However, an HIV-positive person who has an undetectable viral load as a result of long-term treatment has effectively no risk of transmitting HIV sexually, known as Undetectable = Untransmittable.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The existence of functionally noncontagious HIV-positive people on antiretroviral therapy was controversially publicized in the 2008 Swiss Statement, and has since become accepted as medically sound.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Globally, the most common mode of HIV transmission is via sexual contacts between people of the opposite sex; however, the pattern of transmission varies among countries.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] As of 2017, most HIV transmission in the United States occurred among men who had sex with men (82% of new HIV diagnoses among males aged 13 and older and 70% of total new diagnoses).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In the US, gay and bisexual men aged 13 to 24 accounted for an estimated 92% of new HIV diagnoses among all men in their age group and 27% of new diagnoses among all gay and bisexual men.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] With regard to unprotected heterosexual contacts, estimates of the risk of HIV transmission per sexual act appear to be four to ten times higher in low-income countries than in high-income countries.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The risk of transmission from anal intercourse is especially high, estimated as 1.4–1.7% per act in both heterosexual and homosexual contacts.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] While the risk of transmission from oral sex is relatively low, it is still present.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The risk from receiving oral sex has been described as "nearly nil"; however, a few cases have been reported.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The per-act risk is estimated at 0–0.04% for receptive oral intercourse.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In settings involving prostitution in low-income countries, risk of female-to-male transmission has been estimated as 2.4% per act, and of male-to-female transmission as 0.05% per act.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Risk of transmission increases in the presence of many sexually transmitted infections and genital ulcers.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Genital ulcers increase the risk approximately fivefold.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Other sexually transmitted infections, such as gonorrhea, chlamydia, trichomoniasis, and bacterial vaginosis, are associated with somewhat smaller increases in risk of transmission.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The viral load of an infected person is an important risk factor in both sexual and mother-to-child transmission.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] During the first 2.5 months of an HIV infection, a person's infectiousness is twelve times higher due to the high viral load associated with acute HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] If the person is in the late stages of infection, rates of transmission are approximately eightfold greater.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Commercial sex workers (including those in pornography) have an increased likelihood of contracting HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Rough sex can be a factor associated with an increased risk of transmission.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Sexual assault is also believed to carry an increased risk of HIV transmission, as condoms are rarely worn, physical trauma to the vagina or rectum is likely, and there may be a greater risk of concurrent sexually transmitted infections.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The second-most frequent mode of HIV transmission is via blood and blood products.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Blood-borne transmission can be through needle-sharing during intravenous drug use, needle-stick injury, transfusion of contaminated blood or blood product, or medical injections with unsterilized equipment.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The risk from sharing a needle during drug injection is between 0.63% and 2.4% per act, with an average of 0.8%.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The risk of acquiring HIV from a needle stick from an HIV-infected person is estimated as 0.3% (about 1 in 333) per act and the risk following mucous membrane exposure to infected blood as 0.09% (about 1 in 1000) per act.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] This risk may, however, be up to 5% if the introduced blood was from a person with a high viral load and the cut was deep.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In the United States, intravenous drug users made up 12% of all new cases of HIV in 2009, and in some areas more than 80% of people who inject drugs are predicted to be HIV-positive.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV is transmitted in about 90% of blood transfusions using infected blood.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In low-income countries, only half of transfusions may be appropriately screened (as of 2008), and it is estimated that up to 15% of HIV infections in these areas come from transfusion of infected blood and blood products, representing between 5% and 10% of global infections.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] It is possible to acquire HIV from organ and tissue transplantation, although this is rare because of screening.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Unsafe medical injections play a role in HIV spread in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In 2007, between 12% and 17% of infections in this region were attributed to medical syringe use.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The World Health Organization estimates the risk of transmission as a result of a medical injection in Africa at 1.2%.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Risks are also associated with invasive procedures, assisted delivery, and dental care in this area of the world.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] People giving or receiving tattoos, piercings, and scarification are theoretically at risk of infection but no confirmed cases have been documented.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] It is not possible for mosquitoes or other insects to transmit HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV can be transmitted from mother to child during pregnancy, during delivery, or through breast milk, resulting in the baby also contracting HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] As of 2008, vertical transmission accounted for about 90% of cases of HIV in children.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In the absence of treatment, the risk of transmission before or during birth is around 20%, and in those who also breastfeed 35%.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Treatment decreases this risk to less than 5%.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Antiretrovirals when taken by either the mother or the baby decrease the risk of transmission in those who do breastfeed.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] If blood contaminates food during pre-chewing it may pose a risk of transmission.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] If a woman is untreated, two years of breastfeeding results in an HIV/AIDS risk in her baby of about 17%.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Due to the increased risk of death without breastfeeding in many areas in the developing world, the World Health Organization recommends either exclusive breastfeeding or the provision of safe formula.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] All women known to be HIV-positive should be taking lifelong antiretroviral therapy.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV is the cause of the spectrum of disease known as HIV/AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV is a retrovirus that primarily infects components of the human immune system such as CD4+ T cells, macrophages and dendritic cells.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] It directly and indirectly destroys CD4+ T cells.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV is a member of the genus *Lentivirus*, part of the family *Retroviridae*.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Lentiviruses share many morphological and biological characteristics.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Many species of mammals are infected by lentiviruses, which are characteristically responsible for long-duration illnesses with a long incubation period.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Lentiviruses are transmitted as single-stranded, positive-sense, enveloped RNA viruses.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Upon entry into the target cell, the viral RNA genome is converted (reverse transcribed) into double-stranded DNA by a virally encoded reverse transcriptase that is transported along with the viral genome in the virus particle.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The resulting viral DNA is then imported into the cell nucleus and integrated into the cellular DNA by a virally encoded integrase and host co-factors.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Once integrated, the virus may become latent, allowing the virus and its host cell to avoid detection by the immune system.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Alternatively, the virus may be transcribed, producing new RNA genomes and viral proteins that are packaged and released from the cell as new virus particles that begin the replication cycle anew.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV is now known to spread between CD4+ T cells by two parallel routes: cell-free spread and cell-to-cell spread, i.e. it employs hybrid spreading mechanisms.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In the cell-free spread, virus particles bud from an infected T cell, enter the blood/extracellular fluid and then infect another T cell following a chance encounter.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV can also disseminate by direct transmission from one cell to another by a process of cell-to-cell spread.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The hybrid spreading mechanisms of HIV contribute to the virus' ongoing replication against antiretroviral therapies.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Two types of HIV have been characterized: HIV-1 and HIV-2.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV-1 is the virus that was originally discovered (and initially referred to also as LAV or HTLV-III).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] It is more virulent, more infective, and is the cause of the majority of HIV infections globally.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The lower infectivity of HIV-2 as compared with HIV-1 implies that fewer people exposed to HIV-2 will be infected per exposure.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Because of its relatively poor capacity for transmission, HIV-2 is largely confined to West Africa.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] After the virus enters the body, there is a period of rapid viral replication, leading to an abundance of virus in the peripheral blood.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] During primary infection, the level of HIV may reach several million virus particles per milliliter of blood.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] This response is accompanied by a marked drop in the number of circulating CD4+ T cells.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The acute viremia is almost invariably associated with activation of CD8+ T cells, which kill HIV-infected cells, and subsequently with antibody production, or seroconversion.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The CD8+ T cell response is thought to be important in controlling virus levels, which peak and then decline, as the CD4+ T cell counts recover.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] A good CD8+ T cell response has been linked to slower disease progression and a better prognosis, though it does not eliminate the virus.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Ultimately, HIV causes AIDS by depleting CD4+ T cells.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] This weakens the immune system and allows opportunistic infections.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] T cells are essential to the immune response and without them, the body cannot fight infections or kill cancerous cells.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The mechanism of CD4+ T cell depletion differs in the acute and chronic phases.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] During the acute phase, HIV-induced cell lysis and killing of infected cells by CD8+ T cells accounts for CD4+ T cell depletion, although apoptosis may also be a factor.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] During the chronic phase, the consequences of generalized immune activation coupled with the gradual loss of the ability of the immune system to generate new T cells appear to account for the slow decline in CD4+ T cell numbers.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Although the symptoms of immune deficiency characteristic of AIDS do not appear for years after a person is infected, the bulk of CD4+ T cell loss occurs during the first weeks of infection, especially in the intestinal mucosa, which harbors the majority of the lymphocytes found in the body.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The reason for the preferential loss of mucosal CD4+ T cells is that the majority of mucosal CD4+ T cells express the CCR5 protein which HIV uses as a co-receptor to gain access to the cells, whereas only a small fraction of CD4+ T cells in the bloodstream do so.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] A specific genetic change that alters the CCR5 protein when present in both chromosomes very effectively prevents HIV-1 infection.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV seeks out and destroys CCR5 expressing CD4+ T cells during acute infection.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] A vigorous immune response eventually controls the infection and initiates the clinically latent phase.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] CD4+ T cells in mucosal tissues remain particularly affected.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Continuous HIV replication causes a state of generalized immune activation persisting throughout the chronic phase.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Immune activation, which is reflected by the increased activation state of immune cells and release of pro-inflammatory cytokines, results from the activity of several HIV gene products and the immune response to ongoing HIV replication.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] It is also linked to the breakdown of the immune surveillance system of the gastrointestinal mucosal barrier caused by the depletion of mucosal CD4+ T cells during the acute phase of disease.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS related eye diseases are common among people living with this disease worldwide.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Among these diseases, HIV retinopathy is the most common condition.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] This condition is seen in 40% to 60% of HIV positive patients.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] It is also the most common cause of loss of vision in these patients.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS is diagnosed via laboratory testing and then staged based on the presence of certain signs or symptoms.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV screening is recommended by the United States Preventive Services Task Force for all people 15 years to 65 years of age, including all pregnant women.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Additionally, testing is recommended for those at high risk, which includes anyone diagnosed with a sexually transmitted illness.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In many areas of the world, a third of HIV carriers only discover they are infected at an advanced stage of the disease when AIDS or severe immunodeficiency has become apparent.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Most people infected with HIV develop seroconverted (antigen-specific) antibodies within three to twelve weeks after the initial infection.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Diagnosis of primary HIV before seroconversion is done by measuring HIV-RNA or p24 antigen.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Positive results obtained by antibody or PCR testing are confirmed either by a different antibody or by PCR.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Antibody tests in children younger than 18 months are typically inaccurate, due to the continued presence of maternal antibodies.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Thus HIV infection can only be diagnosed by PCR testing for HIV RNA or DNA, or via testing for the p24 antigen.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Much of the world lacks access to reliable PCR testing, and people in many places simply wait until either symptoms develop or the child is old enough for accurate antibody testing.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In sub-Saharan Africa between 2007 and 2009, between 30% and 70% of the population were aware of their HIV status.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In 2009, between 3.6% and 42% of men and women in sub-Saharan countries were tested; this represented a significant increase compared to previous years.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Two main clinical staging systems are used to classify HIV and HIV-related disease for surveillance purposes: the WHO disease staging system for HIV infection and disease, and the CDC classification system for HIV infection.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The CDC's classification system is more frequently adopted in developed countries.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Since the WHO's staging system does not require laboratory tests, it is suited to the resource-restricted conditions encountered in developing countries, where it can also be used to help guide clinical management.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Despite their differences, the two systems allow a comparison for statistical purposes.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The World Health Organization first proposed a definition for AIDS in 1986.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Since then, the WHO classification has been updated and expanded several times, with the most recent version being published in 2007.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention also created a classification system for HIV, and updated it in 2008 and 2014.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] This system classifies HIV infections based on CD4 count and clinical symptoms, and describes the infection in five groups.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] For surveillance purposes, the AIDS diagnosis still stands even if, after treatment, the CD4+ T cell count rises to above 200 per μL of blood or other AIDS-defining illnesses are cured.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Consistent condom use reduces the risk of HIV transmission by approximately 80% over the long term.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] When condoms are used consistently by a couple in which one person is infected, the rate of HIV infection is less than 1% per year.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] There is some evidence to suggest that female condoms may provide an equivalent level of protection.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Application of a vaginal gel containing tenofovir (a reverse transcriptase inhibitor) immediately before sex seems to reduce infection rates by approximately 40% among African women.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] By contrast, use of the spermicide nonoxynol-9 may increase the risk of transmission due to its tendency to cause vaginal and rectal irritation.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Circumcision in sub-Saharan Africa "reduces the acquisition of HIV by heterosexual men by between 38% and 66% over 24 months".
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Owing to these studies, both the World Health Organization and UNAIDS recommended male circumcision in 2007 as a method of preventing female-to-male HIV transmission in areas with high rates of HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] However, whether it protects against male-to-female transmission is disputed, and whether it is of benefit in developed countries and among men who have sex with men is undetermined.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Programs encouraging sexual abstinence do not appear to affect subsequent HIV risk.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Evidence of any benefit from peer education is equally poor.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Comprehensive sexual education provided at school may decrease high-risk behavior.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] A substantial minority of young people continues to engage in high-risk practices despite knowing about HIV/AIDS, underestimating their own risk of becoming infected with HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Voluntary counseling and testing people for HIV does not affect risky behavior in those who test negative but does increase condom use in those who test positive.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Enhanced family planning services appear to increase the likelihood of women with HIV using contraception, compared to basic services.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] It is not known whether treating other sexually transmitted infections is effective in preventing HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Antiretroviral treatment among people with HIV whose CD4 count ≤ 550 cells/μL is a very effective way to prevent HIV infection of their partner (a strategy known as treatment as prevention, or TASP).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] TASP is associated with a 10- to 20-fold reduction in transmission risk.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Pre-exposure prophylaxis for HIV ("PrEP") with a daily dose of the medications tenofovir, with or without emtricitabine, is effective in people at high risk including men who have sex with men, couples where one is HIV-positive, and young heterosexuals in Africa.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] It may also be effective in intravenous drug users, with a study finding a decrease in risk of 0.7 to 0.4 per 100 person years.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The USPSTF, in 2019, recommended PrEP in those who are at high risk.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Universal precautions within the health care environment are believed to be effective in decreasing the risk of HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Intravenous drug use is an important risk factor, and harm reduction strategies such as needle-exchange programs and opioid substitution therapy appear effective in decreasing this risk.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] A course of antiretrovirals administered within 48 to 72 hours after exposure to HIV-positive blood or genital secretions is referred to as post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The use of the single agent zidovudine reduces the risk of an HIV infection five-fold following a needle-stick injury.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] As of 2013, the prevention regimen recommended in the United States consists of three medications—tenofovir, emtricitabine and raltegravir—as this may reduce the risk further.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] PEP treatment is recommended after a sexual assault when the perpetrator is known to be HIV-positive, but is controversial when their HIV status is unknown.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The duration of treatment is usually four weeks and is frequently associated with adverse effects—where zidovudine is used, about 70% of cases result in adverse effects such as nausea (24%), fatigue (22%), emotional distress (13%) and headaches (9%).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Programs to prevent the vertical transmission of HIV (from mothers to children) can reduce rates of transmission by 92–99%.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] This primarily involves the use of a combination of antiviral medications during pregnancy and after birth in the infant, and potentially includes bottle feeding rather than breastfeeding.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] If replacement feeding is acceptable, feasible, affordable, sustainable and safe, mothers should avoid breastfeeding their infants; however, exclusive breastfeeding is recommended during the first months of life if this is not the case.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] If exclusive breastfeeding is carried out, the provision of extended antiretroviral prophylaxis to the infant decreases the risk of transmission.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In 2015, Cuba became the first country in the world to eradicate mother-to-child transmission of HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Currently there is no licensed vaccine for HIV or AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The most effective vaccine trial to date, RV 144, was published in 2009; it found a partial reduction in the risk of transmission of roughly 30%, stimulating some hope in the research community of developing a truly effective vaccine.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS is a chronic condition, as there is currently no cure.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Treatment consists of highly active antiretroviral therapy (ART), which slows progression of the disease.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] As of 2025, 40.9 million people globally were living with HIV, and 32.1 million people were accessing ART.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Treatment also includes preventive and active treatment of opportunistic infections.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] As of July 2022, four people have been successfully cleared of HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Rapid initiation of antiretroviral therapy within one week of diagnosis appear to improve treatment outcomes in low and medium-income settings and is recommend for newly diagnosed HIV patients.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV retinopathy was a very common cause of blindness in people with AIDS before the introduction of highly active antiretroviral therapy, but its incidence is declining due to proper and timely management of AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Even if there are signs of retinopathy, it may reverse as CD4+ T cell counts increase.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Reversal of HIV retinopathy is a helpful sign of positive response to antiretroviral therapy in AIDS patients.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] But if HIV treatment is delayed it may lead to permanent visual loss.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Occurrence of HIV retinopathy may also be an indicator of therapeutic failure in AIDS patients undergoing treatment.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Current ART options are combinations (or "cocktails") consisting of at least three medications belonging to at least two types, or "classes", of antiretroviral agents.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] There are also two drugs, ritonavir (RTV) and cobicistat (COBI) which can be used as pharmacokinetic (PK) enhancers (or boosters) to improve the PK profiles of PIs and the INSTI elvitegravir (EVG).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The World Health Organization and the United States recommend antiretrovirals in people of all ages (including pregnant women) as soon as the diagnosis is made, regardless of CD4 count.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Once treatment is begun, it is recommended that it is continued without breaks or "holidays".
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Many people are diagnosed only after treatment ideally should have begun.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The desired outcome of treatment is a long-term plasma HIV-RNA count below 50 copies/mL.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Levels to determine if treatment is effective are initially recommended after four weeks and once levels fall below 50 copies/mL checks every three to six months are typically adequate.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Inadequate control is deemed to be greater than 400 copies/mL.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Based on these criteria treatment is effective in more than 95% of people during the first year.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Benefits of treatment include a decreased risk of progression to AIDS and a decreased risk of death.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In the developing world, treatment also improves physical and mental health.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] With treatment, there is a 70% reduced risk of acquiring tuberculosis.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Additional benefits include a decreased risk of transmission of the disease to sexual partners and a decrease in mother-to-child transmission.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The effectiveness of treatment depends to a large part on compliance.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Reasons for non-adherence to treatment include poor access to medical care, inadequate social supports, mental illness and drug abuse.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The complexity of treatment regimens (due to pill numbers and dosing frequency) and adverse effects may reduce adherence.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Even though cost is an important issue with some medications, 47% of those who needed them were taking them in low- and middle-income countries as of 2010, and the rate of adherence is similar in low-income and high-income countries.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Specific adverse events are related to the antiretroviral agent taken.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Some relatively common adverse events include: lipodystrophy syndrome, dyslipidemia, and diabetes mellitus, especially with protease inhibitors.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Other common symptoms include diarrhea, and an increased risk of cardiovascular disease.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Newer recommended treatments are associated with fewer adverse effects.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Certain medications may be associated with birth defects and therefore may be unsuitable for women hoping to have children.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Treatment recommendations for children are somewhat different from those for adults.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The World Health Organization recommends treating all children less than five years of age; children above five are treated like adults.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The United States guidelines recommend treating all children less than 12 months of age and all those with HIV RNA counts greater than 100,000 copies/mL between one year and five years of age.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In 2020, the European Medicines Agency recommended approval of a long-acting injectable combination of the antiretrovirals rilpivirine and cabotegravir, marketed as Rekambys and Vocabria; unlike standard daily pills, it is administered by intramuscular injection every one to two months.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] It is indicated as maintenance therapy for adults who are already virologically suppressed (viral load below 50 copies/mL) on a stable regimen, with no documented resistance to non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors or integrase strand transfer inhibitors.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Measures to prevent opportunistic infections are effective in many people with HIV/AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In addition to improving current disease, treatment with antiretrovirals reduces the risk of developing additional opportunistic infections.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Adults and adolescents who are living with HIV (even on anti-retroviral therapy) with no evidence of active tuberculosis in settings with high tuberculosis burden should receive isoniazid preventive therapy (IPT); the tuberculin skin test can be used to help decide if IPT is needed.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Children with HIV may benefit from screening for tuberculosis.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Vaccination against hepatitis A and B is advised for all people at risk of HIV before they become infected; however, it may also be given after infection.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole prophylaxis between four and six weeks of age, and ceasing breastfeeding of infants born to HIV-positive mothers, is recommended in resource-limited settings.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] It is also recommended to prevent PCP when a person's CD4 count is below 200 cells/uL and in those who have or have previously had PCP.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] People with substantial immunosuppression are also advised to receive prophylactic therapy for toxoplasmosis and MAC.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Appropriate preventive measures reduced the rate of these infections by 50% between 1992 and 1997.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Influenza vaccination and pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccine are often recommended in people with HIV/AIDS with some evidence of benefit.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) has issued recommendations regarding nutrient requirements in HIV/AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Dietary intake of micronutrients at RDA levels by HIV-infected adults is recommended by the WHO; higher intake of vitamin A, zinc, and iron can produce adverse effects in HIV-positive adults, and is not recommended unless there is documented deficiency.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Dietary supplementation for people who are infected with HIV and who have inadequate nutrition or dietary deficiencies may strengthen their immune systems or help them recover from infections; however, evidence indicating an overall benefit in morbidity or reduction in mortality is not consistent.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] People with HIV/AIDS are up to four times more likely to develop type 2 diabetes than those who are not tested positive with the virus.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Evidence for supplementation with selenium is mixed with some tentative evidence of benefit.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] For pregnant and lactating women with HIV, multivitamin supplement improves outcomes for both mothers and children.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] If the pregnant or lactating mother has been advised to take anti-retroviral medication to prevent mother-to-child HIV transmission, multivitamin supplements should not replace these treatments.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] There is some evidence that vitamin A supplementation in children with an HIV infection reduces mortality and improves growth.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In the US, approximately 60% of people with HIV use various forms of complementary or alternative medicine, whose effectiveness has not been established.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] There is not enough evidence to support the use of herbal medicines.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] There is insufficient evidence to recommend or support the use of medical cannabis to try to increase appetite or weight gain.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS has become a chronic rather than an acutely fatal disease in many areas of the world.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Prognosis varies between people, and both the CD4 count and viral load are useful for predicted outcomes.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Without treatment, average survival time after infection with HIV is estimated to be 9 to 11 years, depending on the HIV subtype.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] After the diagnosis of AIDS, if treatment is not available, survival ranges between 6 and 19 months.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] ART and appropriate prevention of opportunistic infections reduces the death rate by 80%, and raises the life expectancy for a newly diagnosed young adult to 20–50 years.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] This is between two thirds and nearly that of the general population.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] If treatment is started late in the infection, prognosis is not as good: for example, if treatment is begun following the diagnosis of AIDS, life expectancy is ~10–40 years.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Half of infants born with HIV die before two years of age without treatment.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The primary causes of death from HIV/AIDS are opportunistic infections and cancer, both of which are frequently the result of the progressive failure of the immune system.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Risk of cancer appears to increase once the CD4 count is below 500/μL.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Tuberculosis co-infection is one of the leading causes of sickness and death in those with HIV/AIDS being present in a third of all HIV-infected people and causing 25% of HIV-related deaths.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV is also one of the most important risk factors for tuberculosis.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Hepatitis C is another very common co-infection where each disease increases the progression of the other.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The two most common cancers associated with HIV/AIDS are Kaposi's sarcoma and AIDS-related non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Other cancers that are more frequent include anal cancer, Burkitt's lymphoma, primary central nervous system lymphoma, and cervical cancer.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Even with anti-retroviral treatment, over the long term HIV-infected people may experience neurocognitive disorders, osteoporosis, neuropathy, cancers, nephropathy, and cardiovascular disease.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Some conditions, such as lipodystrophy, may be caused both by HIV and its treatment.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS is considered a global pandemic.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] As of 2025, approximately 40.9 million people worldwide are living with HIV, the number of new infections that year being about 1.2 million.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] This is down 43% from 2.1 million new infections in 2010.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Among new infections, 41% are in women and girls globally.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] There were [CONFIRM 2025 figure] AIDS-related deaths in 2025, down from a peak of 2 million in 2005.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Among persons living with HIV (PLWH), the largest proportion reside in eastern and southern Africa (20.6 million, 54.6%).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] This region also had the highest rate of adult and child deaths due to AIDS in 2020 (310,000, 46.6%).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Sub-Saharan African adolescent girls and young women (aged 15–24 years) account for 77% of new infections among this age-range globally.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Here, in contrast to other regions, adolescent girls and young women are three times more likely to acquire HIV than age-matched males.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Despite these statistics, overall, new HIV infections and AIDS-related deaths have substantially decreased in this region since 2010.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Eastern Europe and central Asia has observed a 43% increase in new HIV infections and 32% increase in AIDS-related deaths since 2010, the highest of all global regions.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] These infections are predominantly distributed in persons who inject drugs, with gay men and other men who have sex with men or persons who engage in transaction sex the second and third populations most impacted in this region.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] At the end of 2019, United States indicated that approximately 1.2 million people aged ≥13 years were living with HIV, resulting in about 18,500 deaths in 2020.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] There were 34,800 estimated new infections in the US in 2019, 53% of which were in the southern region of the country.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In addition to geographic location, significant disparities in HIV incidence exist among men, Black or Hispanic populations, and men who reported male-to-male sexual contact.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention estimated that in that year, 158,500 people or 13% of infected Americans were unaware of their infection.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In the United Kingdom as of 2015, there were approximately 101,200 cases which resulted in 594 deaths.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] In Canada as of 2008, there were about 65,000 cases causing 53 deaths.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Between the first recognition of AIDS (in 1981) and 2009, it has led to nearly 30 million deaths.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Rates of HIV are lowest in North Africa and the Middle East (0.1% or less), East Asia (0.1%), and Western and Central Europe (0.2%).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] The worst-affected European countries, in 2009 and 2012 estimates, are Russia, Ukraine, Latvia, Moldova, Portugal and Belarus, in decreasing order of prevalence.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Groups at higher risk of acquiring HIV include persons who engage in transactional sex, gay men and other men who have sex with men, persons who inject drugs, transgender persons, and those who are incarcerated or detained.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p01] Climate change impacts HIV risk and the availability of and access to HIV prevention and treatment services, and can contribute to poor nutrition, impaired immunity, and poor adherence to treatment.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] The first news story on the disease appeared on May 18, 1981, in the gay newspaper *New York Native*.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] AIDS was first clinically reported on June 5, 1981, with five cases in the United States.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] The initial cases were a cluster of injecting drug users and gay men with no known cause of impaired immunity who showed symptoms of *Pneumocystis carinii* pneumonia (PCP), a rare opportunistic infection that was known to occur in people with very compromised immune systems.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Soon thereafter, a large number of homosexual men developed a generally rare skin cancer called Kaposi's sarcoma (KS).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Many more cases of PCP and KS emerged, alerting the U.S.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and a CDC task force was formed to monitor the outbreak.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] In the early days, the CDC did not have an official name for the disease, often referring to it by way of diseases associated with it, such as lymphadenopathy, the disease after which the discoverers of HIV originally named the virus.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] They also used *Kaposi's sarcoma and opportunistic infections*, the name by which a task force had been set up in 1981.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] At one point the CDC referred to it as the "4H disease", as the syndrome seemed to affect heroin users, homosexuals, hemophiliacs, and Haitians.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] The term *GRID*, which stood for gay-related immune deficiency, had also been coined.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] However, after determining that AIDS was not isolated to the gay community, it was realized that the term *GRID* was misleading, and the term *AIDS* was introduced at a meeting in July 1982.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] By September 1982 the CDC started referring to the disease as AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] In 1983, two separate research groups led by Robert Gallo and Luc Montagnier declared that a novel retrovirus may have been infecting people with AIDS, and published their findings in the same issue of the journal *Science*.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Gallo claimed a virus which his group had isolated from a person with AIDS was strikingly similar in shape to other human T-lymphotropic viruses (HTLVs) that his group had been the first to isolate.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Gallo's group called their newly isolated virus HTLV-III.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] At the same time, Montagnier's group isolated a virus from a person presenting with swelling of the lymph nodes of the neck and physical weakness, two characteristic symptoms of AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Contradicting the report from Gallo's group, Montagnier and his colleagues showed that core proteins of this virus were immunologically different from those of HTLV-I.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Montagnier's group named their isolated virus lymphadenopathy-associated virus (LAV).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] As these two viruses turned out to be the same, in 1986, LAV and HTLV-III were renamed HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] The origin of HIV / AIDS and the circumstances that led to its emergence remain unsolved.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Both HIV-1 and HIV-2 are believed to have originated in non-human primates in West-central Africa and were transferred to humans in the early 20th century.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] HIV-1 appears to have originated in southern Cameroon through the evolution of SIV(cpz), a simian immunodeficiency virus (SIV) that infects wild chimpanzees (HIV-1 descends from the SIVcpz endemic in the chimpanzee subspecies *Pan troglodytes troglodytes*).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] The closest relative of HIV-2 is SIV (smm), a virus of the sooty mangabey (*Cercocebus atys atys*), an Old World monkey living in coastal West Africa (from southern Senegal to western Ivory Coast).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] New World monkeys such as the owl monkey are resistant to HIV-1 infection, possibly because of a genomic fusion of two viral resistance genes.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] HIV-1 is thought to have jumped the species barrier on at least three separate occasions, giving rise to the three groups of the virus, M, N, and O.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] There is evidence that humans who participate in bushmeat activities, either as hunters or as bushmeat vendors, commonly acquire SIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] However, SIV is a weak virus which is typically suppressed by the human immune system within weeks of infection.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] It is thought that several transmissions of the virus from individual to individual in quick succession are necessary to allow it enough time to mutate into HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Furthermore, due to its relatively low person-to-person transmission rate, SIV can only spread throughout the population in the presence of one or more high-risk transmission channels, which are thought to have been absent in Africa before the 20th century.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Specific proposed high-risk transmission channels, allowing the virus to adapt to humans and spread throughout society, depend on the proposed timing of the animal-to-human crossing.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Genetic studies of the virus suggest that the most recent common ancestor of the HIV-1 M group dates back to c.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] While transmission rates of HIV during vaginal intercourse are low under regular circumstances, they are increased manyfold if one of the partners has a sexually transmitted infection causing genital ulcers.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] An alternative view holds that unsafe medical practices in Africa after World War II, such as unsterile reuse of single-use syringes during mass vaccination, antibiotic and anti-malaria treatment campaigns, were the initial vector that allowed the virus to adapt to humans and spread.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] The earliest well-documented case of HIV in a human dates back to 1959 in the Congo.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] The virus may have been present in the U.S. as early as the mid-to-late 1950s.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] A 16-year-old male named Robert Rayford presented with symptoms in 1966 and died in 1969.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] In the 1970s, there were cases of people getting parasites and becoming sick with what was then called "gay bowel disease" but is now suspected to have been AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] The earliest retrospectively described case of AIDS is believed to have been in Norway beginning in 1966, that of Arvid Noe.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] In July 1960, in the wake of Congo's independence, the United Nations recruited Francophone experts and technicians from all over the world to assist in filling administrative gaps left by Belgium, who did not leave behind an African elite to run the country.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] By 1962, Haitians made up the second-largest group of well-educated experts (out of the 48 national groups recruited), that totaled around 4,500 in the country.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Jacques Pépin, a Canadian author of *The Origins of AIDS*, stipulates that Haiti was one of HIV's entry points to the U.S. and that a Haitian may have carried HIV back across the Atlantic in the 1960s.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] The epidemic rapidly spread among high-risk groups (initially, sexually promiscuous men who have sex with men).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] By 1978, the prevalence of HIV-1 among gay male residents of New York City and San Francisco was estimated at 5%, suggesting that several thousand individuals in the country had been infected.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Stigma-related violence or the fear of violence prevents many people from seeking HIV testing, returning for their results, or securing treatment, possibly turning what could be a manageable chronic illness into a death sentence and perpetuating the spread of HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Often, AIDS stigma is expressed in conjunction with one or more other stigmas, particularly those associated with homosexuality, bisexuality, promiscuity, prostitution, and intravenous drug use.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] In many developed countries, there is an association between AIDS and homosexuality or bisexuality, and this association is correlated with higher levels of sexual prejudice, such as anti-homosexual or anti-bisexual attitudes.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] There is also a perceived association between AIDS and all male-male sexual behavior, including sex between uninfected men.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] However, the dominant mode of spread worldwide for HIV remains heterosexual transmission.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] The NAMES Project AIDS Memorial Quilt was conceived in 1985 to celebrate the lives of those who had died of AIDS when stigma prevented many from receiving funerals.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] It is now cared for by the National AIDS Memorial in San Francisco.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] In 2003, as part of an overall reform of marriage and population legislation, it became legal for those diagnosed with AIDS to marry in China.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Between 2004 and 2020, Somen Debnath has travelled the world by bicycle promoting HIV / AIDS awareness.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] National Library of Medicine developed a traveling exhibition titled *Surviving and Thriving: AIDS, Politics, and Culture*; this covered medical research, the U.S. government's response, and personal stories from people with AIDS, caregivers, and activists.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Stigma has proved an obstacle to the update of PrEP.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Within the MSM community, the greatest barrier to PrEP use has been the stigma surrounding HIV and gay men.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Gay men on PrEP have experienced "slut-shaming".
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Numerous other barriers have been identified, including lack of quality LGBTQ care, cost, and adherence to medication use.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] HIV/AIDS affects the economics of both individuals and countries.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] The gross domestic product of the most affected countries has decreased due to the lack of human capital.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Without proper nutrition, health care and medicine, large numbers of people die from AIDS-related complications.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Before death they will not only be unable to work, but will also require significant medical care.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] It is estimated that as of 2007 there were 12 million AIDS orphans.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Many are cared for by elderly grandparents.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Returning to work after beginning treatment for HIV/AIDS is difficult, and affected people often work less than the average worker.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Unemployment in people with HIV/AIDS also is associated with suicidal ideation, memory problems, and social isolation.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Employment increases self-esteem, sense of dignity, confidence, and quality of life for people with HIV/AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Anti-retroviral treatment may help people with HIV/AIDS work more, and may increase the chance that a person with HIV/AIDS will be employed (low-quality evidence).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] By affecting mainly young adults, AIDS reduces the taxable population, in turn reducing the resources available for public expenditures such as education and health services not related to AIDS, resulting in increasing pressure on the state's finances and slower growth of the economy.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] This causes a slower growth of the tax base, an effect that is reinforced if there are growing expenditures on treating the sick, training (to replace sick workers), sick pay, and caring for AIDS orphans.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] This is especially true if the sharp increase in adult mortality shifts the responsibility from the family to the government in caring for these orphans.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] At the household level, AIDS causes both loss of income and increased spending on healthcare.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] A study in Côte d'Ivoire showed that households having a person with HIV/AIDS spent twice as much on medical expenses as other households.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] This additional expenditure also leaves less income to spend on education and other personal or family investment.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] The topic of religion and AIDS has become highly controversial, primarily because some religious authorities have publicly declared their opposition to the use of condoms.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Some religious organizations have claimed that prayer can cure HIV/AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] In 2011, the BBC reported that some churches in London were claiming that prayer would cure AIDS, and the Hackney-based Centre for the Study of Sexual Health and HIV reported that several people stopped taking their medication, sometimes on the direct advice of their pastor, leading to many deaths.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] The Synagogue Church Of All Nations advertised an "anointing water" to promote God's healing, although the group denies advising people to stop taking medication.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] One of the first high-profile cases of AIDS was the American gay actor Rock Hudson.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] He had been diagnosed during 1984, announced that he had had the virus on July 25, 1985, and died a few months later on October 2, 1985.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Another notable British casualty of AIDS that year was Nicholas Eden, a gay politician and son of former prime minister Anthony Eden.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] On November 24, 1991, British rock star Freddie Mercury died from an AIDS-related illness, having revealed the diagnosis only on the previous day.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] One of the first high-profile heterosexual cases of the virus was American tennis player Arthur Ashe.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] He was diagnosed as HIV-positive on August 31, 1988, having contracted the virus from blood transfusions during heart surgery earlier in the 1980s.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Further tests within 24 hours of the initial diagnosis revealed that Ashe had AIDS, but he did not tell the public about his diagnosis until April 1992.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] He died as a result on February 6, 1993, aged 49.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Therese Frare's photograph of gay activist David Kirby, as he lay dying from AIDS while surrounded by family, was taken in April 1990.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] *Life* magazine said the photo became the one image "most powerfully identified with the HIV/AIDS epidemic." The photo was displayed in *Life*, was the winner of the World Press Photo, and acquired worldwide notoriety after being used in a United Colors of Benetton advertising campaign in 1992.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Many famous artists and AIDS activists such as Larry Kramer, Diamanda Galás and Rosa von Praunheim campaign for AIDS education and the rights of those affected.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] These artists worked with various media formats.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Criminal transmission of HIV is the intentional or reckless infection of a person with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Some countries or jurisdictions, including some areas of the United States, have laws that criminalize HIV transmission or exposure.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Others may charge the accused under laws enacted before the HIV pandemic.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] In 1996, Ugandan-born Canadian Johnson Aziga was diagnosed with HIV; he subsequently had unprotected sex with eleven women without disclosing his diagnosis.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] By 2003, seven had contracted HIV; two died from complications related to AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Aziga was convicted of first-degree murder and sentenced to life imprisonment.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] There are many misconceptions about HIV and AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Three misconceptions are that AIDS can spread through casual contact, that sexual intercourse with a virgin will cure AIDS, and that HIV can infect only gay men and drug users.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] In 2014, some among the British public wrongly thought one could get HIV from kissing (16%), sharing a glass (5%), spitting (16%), a public toilet seat (4%), and coughing or sneezing (5%).
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Other misconceptions are that any act of anal intercourse between two uninfected gay men can lead to HIV infection, and that open discussion of HIV and homosexuality in schools will lead to increased rates of AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] A small group of individuals continue to dispute the connection between HIV and AIDS, the existence of HIV itself, or the validity of HIV testing and treatment methods.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] These claims, known as AIDS denialism, have been examined and rejected by the scientific community.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Several discredited conspiracy theories have held that HIV was created by scientists, either inadvertently or deliberately.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Operation INFEKTION was a worldwide Soviet active measures operation to spread the claim that the United States had created HIV/AIDS.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Surveys show that a significant number of people believed—and continue to believe—in such claims.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] HIV/AIDS research includes all medical research which attempts to prevent, treat, or cure HIV/AIDS, along with fundamental research about the nature of HIV as an infectious agent, and about AIDS as the disease caused by HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Many governments and research institutions participate in HIV/AIDS research.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] This research includes behavioral health interventions such as sex education, and drug development, such as research into microbicides for sexually transmitted diseases, HIV vaccines, and antiretroviral drugs.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Other medical research areas include the topics of pre-exposure prophylaxis, post-exposure prophylaxis, and circumcision and HIV.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Public health officials, researchers, and programs can gain a more comprehensive picture of the barriers they face, and the efficacy of current approaches to HIV treatment and prevention, by tracking standard HIV indicators.
[src:transcription-biology/aids-p02] Use of common indicators is an increasing focus of development organizations and researchers.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Both DNA and RNA are nucleic acids, composed of nucleotide sequences.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] During transcription, a DNA sequence is read by an RNA polymerase, which produces a complementary RNA strand called a primary transcript.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In virology, the term transcription is used when referring to mRNA synthesis from a viral RNA molecule.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The genome of many RNA viruses is composed of negative-sense RNA which acts as a template for positive sense viral messenger RNA - a necessary step in the synthesis of viral proteins needed for viral replication.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] This process is catalyzed by a viral RNA dependent RNA polymerase.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] A DNA transcription unit encoding for a protein may contain both a *coding sequence*, which will be translated into the protein, and *regulatory sequences*, which direct and regulate the synthesis of that protein.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The regulatory sequence before (upstream from) the coding sequence is called the five prime untranslated regions (5'UTR); the sequence after (downstream from) the coding sequence is called the three prime untranslated regions (3'UTR).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] As opposed to DNA replication, transcription results in an RNA complement that includes the nucleotide uracil (U) in all instances where thymine (T) would have occurred in a DNA complement.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Only one of the two DNA strands serves as a template for transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The antisense strand of DNA is read by RNA polymerase from the 3' end to the 5' end during transcription (3' → 5').
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The complementary RNA is created in the opposite direction, in the 5' → 3' direction, matching the sequence of the sense strand except switching uracil for thymine.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] This directionality is because RNA polymerase can only add nucleotides to the 3' end of the growing mRNA chain.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] This use of only the 3' → 5' DNA strand eliminates the need for the Okazaki fragments that are seen in DNA replication.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] This also removes the need for an RNA primer to initiate RNA synthesis, as is the case in DNA replication.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The *non*-template (sense) strand of DNA is called the coding strand, because its sequence is the same as the newly created RNA transcript (except for the substitution of uracil for thymine).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] This is the strand that is used by convention when presenting a DNA sequence.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription has some proofreading mechanisms, but they are fewer and less effective than the controls for copying DNA.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] As a result, transcription has a lower copying fidelity than DNA replication.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription is divided into *initiation*, *promoter escape*, *elongation,* and *termination*.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Setting up for transcription in mammals is regulated by many cis-regulatory elements, including core promoter and promoter-proximal elements that are located near the transcription start sites of genes.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Core promoters combined with general transcription factors are sufficient to direct transcription initiation, but generally have low basal activity.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Other important cis-regulatory modules are localized in DNA regions that are distant from the transcription start sites.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] These include enhancers, silencers, insulators and tethering elements.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Among this constellation of elements, enhancers and their associated transcription factors have a leading role in the initiation of gene transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] An enhancer localized in a DNA region distant from the promoter of a gene can have a very large effect on gene transcription, with some genes undergoing up to 100-fold increased transcription due to an activated enhancer.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Enhancers are regions of the genome that are major gene-regulatory elements.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Enhancers control cell-type-specific gene transcription programs, most often by looping through long distances to come in physical proximity with the promoters of their target genes.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] While there are hundreds of thousands of enhancer DNA regions, for a particular type of tissue only specific enhancers are brought into proximity with the promoters that they regulate.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In a study of brain cortical neurons, 24,937 loops were found, bringing enhancers to their target promoters.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Multiple enhancers, each often at tens or hundred of thousands of nucleotides distant from their target genes, loop to their target gene promoters and can coordinate with each other to control transcription of their common target gene.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The schematic illustration in this section shows an enhancer looping around to come into close physical proximity with the promoter of a target gene.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The loop is stabilized by a dimer of a connector protein (e.g. dimer of CTCF or YY1), with one member of the dimer anchored to its binding motif on the enhancer and the other member anchored to its binding motif on the promoter (represented by the red zigzags in the illustration).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Mediator (a complex usually consisting of about 26 proteins in an interacting structure) communicates regulatory signals from enhancer DNA-bound transcription factors directly to the RNA polymerase II (pol II) enzyme bound to the promoter.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Enhancers, when active, are generally transcribed from both strands of DNA with RNA polymerases acting in two different directions, producing two enhancer RNAs (eRNAs) as illustrated in the Figure.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] An inactive enhancer may be bound by an inactive transcription factor.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Phosphorylation of the transcription factor may activate it and that activated transcription factor may then activate the enhancer to which it is bound (see small red star representing phosphorylation of transcription factor bound to enhancer in the illustration).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] An activated enhancer begins transcription of its RNA before activating transcription of messenger RNA from its target gene.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription regulation at about 60% of promoters is also controlled by methylation of cytosines within CpG dinucleotides (where 5' cytosine is followed by 3' guanine or CpG sites).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] 5-methylcytosine (5-mC) is a methylated form of the DNA base cytosine (see Figure).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] 5-mC is an epigenetic marker found predominantly within CpG sites.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] About 28 million CpG dinucleotides occur in the human genome.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In most tissues of mammals, on average, 70% to 80% of CpG cytosines are methylated (forming 5-methylCpG or 5-mCpG).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] However, unmethylated cytosines within 5'cytosine-guanine 3' sequences often occur in groups, called CpG islands, at active promoters.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] About 60% of promoter sequences have a CpG island while only about 6% of enhancer sequences have a CpG island.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] CpG islands constitute regulatory sequences, since if CpG islands are methylated in the promoter of a gene this can reduce or silence gene transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] DNA methylation regulates gene transcription through interaction with methyl binding domain (MBD) proteins, such as MeCP2, MBD1 and MBD2.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] These MBD proteins bind most strongly to highly methylated CpG islands.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] These MBD proteins have both a methyl-CpG-binding domain as well as a transcription repression domain.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] They bind to methylated DNA and guide or direct protein complexes with chromatin remodeling and/or histone modifying activity to methylated CpG islands.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] MBD proteins generally repress local chromatin such as by catalyzing the introduction of repressive histone marks, or creating an overall repressive chromatin environment through nucleosome remodeling and chromatin reorganization.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] As noted in the previous section, transcription factors are proteins that bind to specific DNA sequences in order to regulate the expression of a gene.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The binding sequence for a transcription factor in DNA is usually about 10 or 11 nucleotides long.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] As summarized in 2009, Vaquerizas et al. indicated there are approximately 1,400 different transcription factors encoded in the human genome by genes that constitute about 6% of all human protein encoding genes.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] About 94% of transcription factor binding sites (TFBSs) that are associated with signal-responsive genes occur in enhancers while only about 6% of such TFBSs occur in promoters.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] EGR1 protein is a particular transcription factor that is important for regulation of methylation of CpG islands.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] An EGR1 transcription factor binding site is frequently located in enhancer or promoter sequences.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] There are about 12,000 binding sites for EGR1 in the mammalian genome and about half of EGR1 binding sites are located in promoters and half in enhancers.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The binding of EGR1 to its target DNA binding site is insensitive to cytosine methylation in the DNA.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] While only small amounts of EGR1 transcription factor protein are detectable in cells that are un-stimulated, translation of the *EGR1* gene into protein at one hour after stimulation is drastically elevated.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Production of EGR1 transcription factor proteins, in various types of cells, can be stimulated by growth factors, neurotransmitters, hormones, stress and injury.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In the brain, when neurons are activated, EGR1 proteins are up-regulated and they bind to (recruit) the pre-existing TET1 enzymes that are produced in high amounts in neurons.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] TET enzymes can catalyse demethylation of 5-methylcytosine.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] When EGR1 transcription factors bring TET1 enzymes to EGR1 binding sites in promoters, the TET enzymes can demethylate the methylated CpG islands at those promoters.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Upon demethylation, these promoters can then initiate transcription of their target genes.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Hundreds of genes in neurons are differentially expressed after neuron activation through EGR1 recruitment of TET1 to methylated regulatory sequences in their promoters.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The methylation of promoters is also altered in response to signals.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The three mammalian DNA methyltransferasess (DNMT1, DNMT3A, and DNMT3B) catalyze the addition of methyl groups to cytosines in DNA.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] While DNMT1 is a maintenance methyltransferase, DNMT3A and DNMT3B can carry out new methylations.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] There are also two splice protein isoforms produced from the *DNMT3A* gene: DNA methyltransferase proteins DNMT3A1 and DNMT3A2.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The splice isoform DNMT3A2 behaves like the product of a classical immediate-early gene and, for instance, it is robustly and transiently produced after neuronal activation.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Where the DNA methyltransferase isoform DNMT3A2 binds and adds methyl groups to cytosines appears to be determined by histone post translational modifications.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] On the other hand, neural activation causes degradation of DNMT3A1 accompanied by reduced methylation of at least one evaluated targeted promoter.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The regulatory sequence elements (yellow) at the start of a eukaryotic protein-coding gene, can be immediately upstream of the open read frame (ORF, red), or many kilobases away (upstream or downstream).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Promoter and enhancer regions up-regulate (and silencers downregulate) transcription from DNA to mRNA.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The 5' and 3' untranslated regions of that mRNA (UTR, blue) then regulate translation into the final protein product.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] During transcription initiation, proteins (dark grey semi-circles) bound to the DNA can be brought into proximity with each other since the intervening DNA can loop back on itself.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In this way, the basal transcription machinery can interact with distant activators and repressors many kilobases upstream or downstream of the open reading frame.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription begins with the RNA polymerase and one or more general transcription factors binding to a DNA promoter sequence to form an RNA polymerase-promoter closed complex.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In the closed complex, the promoter DNA is still fully double-stranded.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] RNA polymerase, assisted by one or more general transcription factors, then unwinds approximately 14 base pairs of DNA to form an RNA polymerase-promoter open complex.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In the open complex, the promoter DNA is partly unwound and single-stranded.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The exposed, single-stranded DNA is referred to as the "transcription bubble".
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In bacteria, the RNA polymerase core enzyme consists of five subunits: 2 α subunits, 1 β subunit, 1 β' subunit, and 1 ω subunit.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] It binds to a single transcription factor, called the sigma factor, and together they make up the RNA polymerase holoenzyme.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Unlike in eukaryotes, the initiating nucleotide of nascent bacterial mRNA is not capped with a modified guanine nucleotide.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] It instead bears a 5′ triphosphate (5′-PPP), which can be used for genome-wide mapping of transcription initiation sites.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In archaea and eukaryotes, RNA polymerase contains subunits homologous to each of the five bacterial RNA polymerase subunits as well as unique ones.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Instead of a single sigma factor, multiple general transcription factors are required to initiate transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Archaea have three general transcription factors: TBP, TFB, and TFE.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In eukaryotes, RNA polymerase II requires six general transcription factors: TFIIA, TFIIB (an ortholog of archaeal TFB), TFIID (a multisubunit factor in which the key subunit, TBP, is an ortholog of archaeal TBP), TFIIE (an ortholog of archaeal TFE), TFIIF, and TFIIH.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The TBP subunit of TFIID is the first to bind to DNA, while TFIIH is the last component to be recruited.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In archaea and eukaryotes, the RNA polymerase-promoter closed complex is usually referred to as the "preinitiation complex".
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription initiation is regulated by additional proteins, known as activators and repressors, and, in some cases, associated coactivators or corepressors, which modulate formation and function of the transcription initiation complex.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] After the first bond is synthesized, RNA polymerase must escape the promoter.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] During this time there is a tendency to release the RNA transcript and produce truncated transcripts.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] This is called abortive initiation, and is common for both eukaryotes and prokaryotes.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Abortive initiation continues to occur until an RNA product of a threshold length of approximately 10 nucleotides is synthesized, at which point promoter escape occurs and a transcription elongation complex is formed.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Mechanistically, promoter escape occurs through DNA scrunching, providing the energy needed to break interactions between RNA polymerase holoenzyme and the promoter.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In bacteria, it was historically thought that the sigma factor is definitely released after promoter clearance occurs.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] This theory had been known as the *obligate release model.* However, later data showed that upon and following promoter clearance, the sigma factor is released according to a stochastic model known as the *stochastic release model*.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In eukaryotes, at an RNA polymerase II-dependent promoter, upon promoter clearance, TFIIH phosphorylates serine 5 on the carboxy terminal domain of RNA polymerase II, leading to the recruitment of capping enzyme (CE).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The exact mechanism of how CE induces promoter clearance in eukaryotes is not yet known.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] One strand of the DNA, the *template strand* (or noncoding strand), is used as a template for RNA synthesis.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] As transcription proceeds, RNA polymerase traverses the template strand and uses base pairing complementarity with the DNA template to create an RNA copy (which elongates during the traversal).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Although RNA polymerase traverses the template strand from 3' → 5', the coding (non-template) strand and newly formed RNA can also be used as reference points, so transcription can be described as occurring 5' → 3'.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] This produces an RNA molecule from 5' → 3', an exact copy of the coding strand (except that thymines are replaced with uracils, and the nucleotides are composed of a ribose (5-carbon) sugar whereas DNA has deoxyribose (one fewer oxygen atom) in its sugar-phosphate backbone).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] mRNA transcription can involve multiple RNA polymerases on a single DNA template and multiple rounds of transcription (amplification of particular mRNA), so many mRNA molecules can be rapidly produced from a single copy of a gene.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The characteristic elongation rates in prokaryotes and eukaryotes are about 10–100 nts/sec.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In eukaryotes, however, nucleosomes act as major barriers to transcribing polymerases during transcription elongation.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In these organisms, the pausing induced by nucleosomes can be regulated by transcription elongation factors such as TFIIS.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Elongation also involves a proofreading mechanism that can replace incorrectly incorporated bases.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In eukaryotes, this may correspond with short pauses during transcription that allow appropriate RNA editing factors to bind.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] These pauses may be intrinsic to the RNA polymerase or due to chromatin structure.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Double-strand breaks in actively transcribed regions of DNA are repaired by homologous recombination during the S and G2 phases of the cell cycle.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Since transcription enhances the accessibility of DNA to exogenous chemicals and internal metabolites that can cause recombinogenic lesions, homologous recombination of a particular DNA sequence may be strongly stimulated by transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Bacteria use two different strategies for transcription termination – Rho-independent termination and Rho-dependent termination.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In Rho-independent transcription termination, RNA transcription stops when the newly synthesized RNA molecule forms a G-C-rich hairpin loop followed by a run of Us.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] When the hairpin forms, the mechanical stress breaks the weak rU-dA bonds, now filling the DNA–RNA hybrid.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] This pulls the poly-U transcript out of the active site of the RNA polymerase, terminating transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In Rho-dependent termination, Rho, a protein factor, destabilizes the interaction between the template and the mRNA, thus releasing the newly synthesized mRNA from the elongation complex.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription termination in eukaryotes is less well understood than in bacteria, but involves cleavage of the new transcript followed by template-independent addition of adenines at its new 3' end, in a process called polyadenylation.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Beyond termination by a terminator sequences (which is a part of a gene), transcription may also need to be terminated when it encounters conditions such as DNA damage or an active replication fork.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In bacteria, the Mfd ATPase can remove a RNA polymerase stalled at a lesion by prying open its clamp.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] It also recruits nucleotide excision repair machinery to repair the lesion.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Mfd is proposed to also resolve conflicts between DNA replication and transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In eukayrotes, ATPase TTF2 helps to suppress the action of RNAP I and II during mitosis, preventing errors in chromosomal segregation.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In archaea, the Eta ATPase is proposed to play a similar role.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Genome damage occurs with a high frequency, estimated to range between tens and hundreds of thousands of DNA damages arising in each cell every day.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The process of transcription is a major source of DNA damage, due to the formation of single-strand DNA intermediates that are vulnerable to damage.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The regulation of transcription by processes using base excision repair and/or topoisomerases to cut and remodel the genome also increases the vulnerability of DNA to damage.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] RNA polymerase plays a very crucial role in all steps including post-transcriptional changes in RNA.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] As shown in the image in the right it is evident that the CTD (C Terminal Domain) is a tail that changes its shape; this tail will be used as a carrier of splicing, capping and polyadenylation, as shown in the image on the left.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription inhibitors can be used as antibiotics against, for example, pathogenic bacteria (antibacterials) and fungi (antifungals).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] An example of such an antibacterial is rifampicin, which inhibits bacterial transcription of DNA into mRNA by inhibiting DNA-dependent RNA polymerase by binding its beta-subunit, while 8-hydroxyquinoline is an antifungal transcription inhibitor.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The effects of histone methylation may also work to inhibit the action of transcription.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Potent, bioactive natural products like triptolide that inhibit mammalian transcription via inhibition of the XPB subunit of the general transcription factor TFIIH has been recently reported as a glucose conjugate for targeting hypoxic cancer cells with increased glucose transporter production.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In vertebrates, the majority of gene promoters contain a CpG island with numerous CpG sites.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] When many of a gene's promoter CpG sites are methylated the gene becomes inhibited (silenced).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Colorectal cancers typically have 3 to 6 driver mutations and 33 to 66 hitchhiker or passenger mutations.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] However, transcriptional inhibition (silencing) may be of more importance than mutation in causing progression to cancer.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] For example, in colorectal cancers about 600 to 800 genes are transcriptionally inhibited by CpG island methylation (see regulation of transcription in cancer).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Transcriptional repression in cancer can also occur by other epigenetic mechanisms, such as altered production of microRNAs.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In breast cancer, transcriptional repression of BRCA1 may occur more frequently by over-produced microRNA-182 than by hypermethylation of the BRCA1 promoter (see Low expression of BRCA1 in breast and ovarian cancers).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Active transcription units are clustered in the nucleus, in discrete sites called transcription factories or euchromatin.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Such sites can be visualized by allowing engaged polymerases to extend their transcripts in tagged precursors (Br-UTP or Br-U) and immuno-labeling the tagged nascent RNA.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription factories can also be localized using fluorescence in situ hybridization or marked by antibodies directed against polymerases.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] There are ≈10,000 factories in the nucleoplasm of a HeLa cell, among which are ≈8,000 polymerase II factories and ≈2,000 polymerase III factories.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Each polymerase II factory contains ≈8 polymerases.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] As most active transcription units are associated with only one polymerase, each factory usually contains ≈8 different transcription units.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] These units might be associated through promoters and/or enhancers, with loops forming a "cloud" around the factor.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] A molecule that allows the genetic material to be realized as a protein was first hypothesized by François Jacob and Jacques Monod.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Severo Ochoa won a Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1959 for developing a process for synthesizing RNA *in vitro* with polynucleotide phosphorylase, which was useful for cracking the genetic code.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] RNA synthesis by RNA polymerase was established *in vitro* by several laboratories by 1965; however, the RNA synthesized by these enzymes had properties that suggested the existence of an additional factor needed to terminate transcription correctly.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Kornberg won the 2006 Nobel Prize in Chemistry "for his studies of the molecular basis of eukaryotic transcription".
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Some viruses (such as HIV, the cause of AIDS), have the ability to transcribe RNA into DNA.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] HIV has an RNA genome that is *reverse transcribed* into DNA.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The resulting DNA can be merged with the DNA genome of the host cell.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The main enzyme responsible for synthesis of DNA from an RNA template is called reverse transcriptase.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In the case of HIV, reverse transcriptase is responsible for synthesizing a complementary DNA strand (cDNA) to the viral RNA genome.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The enzyme ribonuclease H then digests the RNA strand, and reverse transcriptase synthesises a complementary strand of DNA to form a double helix DNA structure (cDNA).
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The cDNA is integrated into the host cell's genome by the enzyme integrase, which causes the host cell to generate viral proteins that reassemble into new viral particles.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] In HIV, subsequent to this, the host cell undergoes programmed cell death, or apoptosis, of T cells.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] However, in other retroviruses, the host cell remains intact as the virus buds out of the cell.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Some eukaryotic cells contain an enzyme with reverse transcription activity called telomerase.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Telomerase carries an RNA template from which it synthesizes a telomere, a repeating sequence of DNA, to the end of linear chromosomes.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] It is important because every time a linear chromosome is duplicated, it is shortened.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] With the telomere at the ends of chromosomes, the shortening eliminates some of the non-essential, repeated sequence, rather than the protein-encoding DNA sequence farther away from the chromosome end.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Telomerase is often activated in cancer cells to enable cancer cells to duplicate their genomes indefinitely without losing important protein-coding DNA sequence.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] Activation of telomerase could be part of the process that allows cancer cells to become immortal.
[src:transcription-biology/transcription-biology] The immortalizing factor of cancer via telomere lengthening due to telomerase has been proven to occur in 90% of all carcinogenic tumors *in vivo* with the remaining 10% using an alternative telomere maintenance route called ALT or Alternative Lengthening of Telomeres.
